    "lp_problem": {
      "type": "aliange-lp-text-block",
      "settings": {
        "label": "The Science",
        "headline": "Why Your Skin Looks Dull",
        "body": "<p>Dull skin is a common concern that can be caused by a variety of factors. One of the primary culprits is a slowdown in cell turnover. In our youth, our skin naturally renews itself every 28 days, but <strong>by our 50s, this process can slow to as long as 60 days</strong>. This means that dead, pigmented skin cells remain on the surface for longer, obscuring the fresh, new cells beneath and leading to a lacklustre complexion.</p><p>Another key factor is a compromised skin barrier. A healthy skin barrier is essential for retaining moisture and protecting the skin from environmental aggressors. When the barrier is weakened, it can lead to dehydration, inflammation, and a loss of radiance. In fact, <strong>Niacinamide has been shown to boost ceramide production by up to 5.5x</strong>, which is crucial for a radiant complexion.</p><p>Finally, oxidative stress from sun exposure, pollution, and other environmental factors can also contribute to dullness. For example, the Australian native <strong>Kakadu Plum contains up to 100 times more Vitamin C than oranges</strong>, providing potent antioxidant defence.</p>",
        "bg": "muted",
        "width": "narrow",
        "cta_text": "",
        "cta_url": "",
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/Generated_Image_March_24_2026_-_11_58AM.jpg",
        "image_position": "right"
      }
    },
